is possibly 'undefined'.
optional chaining

### 🕗 Version & Regression Information

Verified bugged in 4.9.5 through 5.0.4 and the most recent Nightly as of this posting.

(The same code throws a different ts error earlier than 4.9.5.)

### ⏯ Playground Link

[Playground link with relevant code](https://www.typescriptlang.org/play?#code/JYOwLgpgTgZghgYwgAgGIHt3IN4ChkHIyYBcO+hlcZAzmFKAOYDcFlBARrfU65QL59CHOFG4MQLXP1y4IADwAO6KGGQATCPACuAGzUxtIBGGDoQyRhDAAhUQAp0HAFZkMWAD7IjmmKAjqAJTiTOSUCOZ0RJjIALzITs4A-AB0xOhCBBEgUXBx0eipcJnIwDDI9gCEcIFh7ARgABZQ6ADuyCAQ7QCiUC1Q9gBEAJIgAG5wusDqyKKMNIOBJTJsyFDW2lAWiSkiUMzIAPSHyAA8ALSXCS6lNMjKNDTAHLooPlr+M43QKIgRUOpQmAsGAaAhkBAxhALE10NpGI1SmoEHALJ0oVA1hBJroAJ7IDgQaRAA)

### 💻 Code

<!-- Please post the relevant code sample here as well-->
```ts
interface Foo {
    foo: {
        a: string;
        b: string;
    };
    bar: string;
}

export default function getBar(obj: Foo | undefined): string {
    const foo = obj?.foo;
    const a = foo?.a;
    if (!a) {
        throw new Error("Invalid args");
    }

    return obj.bar; // <--- obj is possible undefined here according to tsc even though it can never really be
}
```

### 🙁 Actual behavior

`'obj' is possibly 'undefined'.(18048)` at the final return line for 'obj'

### 🙂 Expected behavior

No typescript error should be shown here, because 'obj' can never be undefined since 'foo' and 'a' would then also be undefined so the code would never reach the final return.

